This story is available exclusively to Insider subscribers.  Become an Insider and start reading now.
  For three years until his departure this January, Simon McLaren served as the director of communications for Blade, the urban aviation startup that went public earlier this year at a valuation of more than $800 million. His work in that time was largely what you&#39;d expect of a company spokesperson — except for the fact that Simon McLaren doesn&#39;t actually exist.
 After Insider sought to verify McLaren&#39;s identity, Blade CEO Rob Wiesenthal admitted in an interview that McLaren was a made-up persona invented by him and his colleagues, and that Wiesenthal masqueraded as McLaren in telephone conversations with news outlets. The ruse lasted for years, duped numerous journalists, and included a puzzling public drama around McLaren&#39;s purported departure from Blade. None of it was real.
  McLaren has no substantial online presence outside of  a Blade email address, a  Twitter account created last December, and  a Medium profile created last November. His  personal website, created this January, was registered through a proxy, and he uses a 1966 photo of British racing driver Graham Hill across his accounts in place of a profile picture.
 Still, McLaren has been treated as a real human by a variety of news outlets since his apparent debut in the pages of  Vanity Fair in 2018. Serving as the institutional voice of Blade in stories about the company&#39;s compliance with federal regulations, medical supply shuttles, and negotiations with the town of East Hampton, McLaren has been quoted by the  New York Times, the  New York Post,  Curbed, the  Washington Post,  Fox Business, and  CNN .
 McLaren&#39;s most recent  official press release appears to have been sent out in November 2020, just as Blade began searching for outside representation. But his voice continued to live on in the form of short, opinionated blog posts, called &#34;Simon McLaren&#39;s Curious Content,&#34;  that Blade began sending to subscribers of its email list in October 2020. For twelve weeks, McLaren — under Blade&#39;s logo — weighed in on a number of pandemic issues, including  moving to Miami,  meeting over Zoom, and  patronizing New York restaurants.
  In June, Insider attempted to reach McLaren at a Westchester phone number that he had previously used to call an Insider reporter for  an August 2020 interview, and had been  publicized as belonging to McLaren on the Blade Twitter account in 2019. The call was answered by Lee Gold, Blade&#39;s chief of staff.
 Asked why he was answering McLaren&#39;s phone, Gold said, &#34;I schedule for Simon as well.&#34; He added that he had met McLaren in person and that even though McLaren was no longer on staff at Blade, &#34;he sometimes will do some freelancing for us as a spokesperson.&#34;
 Gold agreed to schedule an interview with McLaren, asking Insider to send a request via email. In a follow-up call, Gold said he hadn&#39;t seen McLaren in months and that an email to McLaren&#39;s address had bounced back. He then appeared to block this reporter&#39;s number. Reached again, he declined to answer further questions about McLaren.
     Soon after, Insider received a call from Rob Wiesenthal, who admitted to inventing McLaren. He described the practice of creating false personas and conducting interviews with reporters under false pretenses as a common practice among small companies.
 &#34;As a small company, everyone has to wear many hats. When it was appropriate for a spokesman to respond to a press inquiry, rather than the CEO, given that we did not have a spokesman, we used the pseudonym,&#34; Wiesenthal said. He claimed that, with the exception of McLaren&#39;s name and identity, the spokesman always told the truth. &#34;In the summer of 2020, as a private company we stopped using the press inquiry pseudonym and we now have an outside firm representing us, and we apologize to anyone who feels deceived when we used a pseudonym.&#34;
 The McLaren persona initially started out as a solution to a small, untrained team, Wiesenthal said. &#34;I&#39;m the only person who would speak to the press, unless by email directed by me. We just did not have a spokesperson and people had to wear many hats,&#34; he said. &#34;There was no intention of being duplicitous. A lot of people wanted a name for a spokesman, and it was just not appropriate for a CEO to speak. And a lot of people didn&#39;t have training on how to speak with the press. There are a lot of small companies that have done this and continue to do this, but at a certain point you outgrow it, and we outgrew it.&#34;
 Wiesenthal said McLaren&#39;s career as a blogger and newsletter writer was a secondary project that evolved out of the pandemic, in part to keep Blade&#39;s marketing and creative teams busy.
 &#34;During the dark days of Covid, I really think it kept people going,&#34; Wiesenthal said. &#34;We had weeks where nothing was flying during the lockdown. But people wanted to engage and get people to work and communicate with our flyers, we weren&#39;t going to say, &#39;Fly to the airport.&#39; So we wrote interesting things about what life was like in the city.&#34;
  A former Sony executive and lifelong New Yorker, Wiesenthal stepped down as the chief operating officer of Warner Music to launch Blade in 2015. The company, which describes itself as an &#34;urban air mobility platform&#34; and brokers flights on helicopters and chartered jets, attracted investments from heavyweights like Barry Diller and David Geffen before going public by merging with a    SPAC  earlier this year. It now trades on the Nasdaq.
 The SPAC deal coincided with McLaren&#39;s official exit from Blade. In January 2021, just a few weeks after the company tapped the communications firm ICR to announce the merger, Blade sent out an unusual letter to subscribers explaining that McLaren would be leaving the company, and taking the newsletter with him, in part because he could no longer abide Blade&#39;s attempts to edit his views.
 &#34;We are living in a uniquely polarizing time,&#34; the statement said. &#34;As such, despite how much we enjoy Simon McLaren&#39;s Curious Content and his unique perspective on what it&#39;s like to be a diehard New Yorker in this day and age, both Simon and the Company have decided that it&#39;s best that we part ways and transition his weekly newsletter from Blade to him.&#34;
     The letter quoted McLaren explaining that he was no longer an appropriate spokesperson for Blade. &#34;My weekly dispatches have little interest to me or my readers unless they create emotion — laughter or perhaps annoyance, and at times, happiness or even unexpected animus. I appreciate the platform Blade has given me, but I am at the point in my life where I have little interest in Blade, or its partners, bleaching my prose in an effort to avoid any readers potentially being triggered by my views. Over the past few weeks, Blade&#39;s editing process has created the literary equivalent of melba toast. Simply put, my views are not subject to negotiation.&#34;
 Wiesenthal said the drama around McLaren&#39;s seemingly rocky departure started as an &#34;inside joke&#34; among the company&#39;s creative team.
 Whether he exists or not, McLaren was certainly on the money about one thing: In January, he predicted that stories about well known public figures pretending to be someone they were not would be big in 2021.
 &#34;Given the giant void created by our departing president, news outlets will be starving for stories to report on. How inconsequential a story will the media be willing to cover?&#34; he wrote. &#34;Well, consider this. How many stories have you read in the past 72 hours about the allegedly fake Spanish accent of Alec Baldwin&#39;s wife? Yes, that&#39;s a story that will qualify for &#39;above the fold&#39; status in 2021.&#34;
